07838nam a22019695i 9780691222387DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020044599  a97806912223877 a10.1515/97806912223872doi  a(DE-B1597)585351  a(OCoLC)1262320906  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBH221.E853 4aBH221.E853bB37 2021 7aART0150802bisacsh04a364.1/209409022231 aBarkan, Leonard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hungry Eye :bEating, Drinking, and European Culture from Rome to the Renaissance /cLeonard Barkan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b210 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One Reading for the Food -- tChapter Two Rome Eats -- tChapter Three Fooding the Bible -- tChapter Four The Debate over Dinner -- tChapter Five Mimesis, Metaphor, Embodiment -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tImage Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn enticing history of food and drink in Western art and cultureEating and drinking can be aesthetic experiences as well as sensory ones. The Hungry Eye takes readers from antiquity to the Renaissance to explore the central role of food and drink in literature, art, philosophy, religion, and statecraft.In this beautifully illustrated book, Leonard Barkan provides an illuminating meditation on how culture finds expression in what we eat and drink. Plato's Symposium is a timeless philosophical text, one that also describes a drinking party. Salome performed her dance at a banquet where the head of John the Baptist was presented on a platter. Barkan looks at ancient mosaics, Dutch still life, and Venetian Last Suppers. He describes how ancient Rome was a paradise of culinary obsessives, and explains what it meant for the Israelites to dine on manna. He discusses the surprising relationship between Renaissance perspective and dinner parties, and sheds new light on the moment when the risen Christ appears to his disciples hungry for a piece of broiled fish. Readers will browse the pages of the Deipnosophistae—an ancient Greek work in sixteen volumes about a single meal, complete with menus—and gain epicurean insights into such figures as Rabelais and Shakespeare, Leonardo and Vermeer.A book for anyone who relishes the pleasures of the table, The Hungry Eye is an erudite and uniquely personal look at all the glorious ways that food and drink have transfigured Western arts and high culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAesthetics, European. 0aArts, EuropeanxThemes, motives. 0aDinners and diningzEuropexHistory. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAgathon.  aApicius.  aApple of Discord.  aBalsamic vinegar.  aBaptistery.  aBartolomeo Scappi.  aBathos.  aBroth.  aCarneades.  aCarpaccio.  aCockaigne.  aColloquies.  aCookbook.  aCooking.  aCoriander.  aCosimo de' Medici.  aCuisine.  aDeipnosophistae.  aDelicacy.  aDrinking.  aElegant variation.  aEncomium.  aEpicurus.  aErudition.  aFoie gras.  aFoodie.  aFrançois Rabelais.  aFritter.  aGambero Rosso.  aGarum.  aGastronomy.  aGenre.  aGiovanni Bellini.  aGiulio Romano.  aGluttony.  aGorgias.  aHigh Renaissance.  aHigh culture.  aIconography.  aIngredient.  aIntinction.  aJoachim Beuckelaer.  aJuvenal.  aLate Antiquity.  aLiterature.  aLoeb Classical Library.  aLucretius.  aLunch.  aMead.  aMeal.  aMetaphor.  aMince pie.  aMoralia.  aNarrative.  aNecromancy.  aOtium.  aPaolo Veronese.  aParody.  aPastry.  aPhilosophy.